AB Tasks in visual analytics differ from typical information retrieval
   tasks in fundamental ways. A critical part of a visual analytics is to
   ask the right questions when dealing with a diverse collection of
   information. In this article, we introduce the design and application
   of an integrated exploratory visualization system called Storylines.
   Storylines provides a framework to enable analysts visually and
   systematically explore and study a body of unstructured text without
   prior knowledge of its thematic structure. The system innovatively
   integrates latent semantic indexing, natural language processing, and
   social network analysis. The contributions of the work include
   providing an intuitive and directly accessible representation of a
   latent semantic space derived from the text corpus, an integrated
   process for identifying salient lines of stories, and coordinated
   visualizations across a spectrum of perspectives in terms of people,
   locations, and events involved in each story line. The system is tested
   with the 2006 VAST contest data, in particular, the portion of news
   articles. 
