AB In this article we demonstrate the use of an integrative approach to
   visualizing and tracking the development of scientific paradigms. This
   approach is designed to reveal the long-term process of competing
   scientific paradigms. We assume that a cluster of highly cited and
   cocited scientific publications in a cocitation network represents the
   core of a predominant scientific paradigm. The growth of a paradigm is
   depicted and animated through the rise of citation rates and the
   movement of its core cluster towards the center of the cocitation
   network. We study two cases of competing scientific paradigms in the
   real world: (1) the causes of mass extinctions, and (2) the connections
   between mad cow disease and a new variant of a brain disease in
   humans-vCJD. Various theoretical and practical issues concerning this
   approach are discussed.
